1. Remember when I said we might be able to lure the Blue Reverberation using a theoretical book of the Red Mist?
2. I wouldn’t do such a ruthless thing.
3. There’s a few things the Red Mist left behind, and I could use them to invite the Red Mist in her former glory as our guest.
4. I think I could recreate her somehow.
5. Though she can only exist within the bounds of the Library, of course.
6. I suppose you could put it that way.
7. …Books about Lobotomy Corporation.
8. And I plan to limit certain Patron Librarians from receiving the Red Mist.
9. That’s not the reason, no. Could the Red Mist stomach wielding her blade against those she worked with?
10. It’d clearly have adverse effects on both sides.
11. It’s intriguing indeed. How does it feel?
12. This is my first time seeing you in this form, Gebura.
13. That’s a fair reaction, I suppose…
14. Should I call you Kali, then?
15. I’m Angela, the director and librarian of my role’s namesake. I invited you here.
16. I need to know who you exactly are at the moment, so let me ask you a few questions.
17. Do you happen to have acquaintance with a person named Carmen?
18. There’s no need to be so wary.
19. Answer a few questions of mine, then I can give you the answer you lot are looking for.
20. …Cogito. A book containing the information on how to obtain the substance you’re desperately looking for is waiting beyond this door.
21. I simply want to make an offer.
22. It’s simple. First, I want to know the current situation of your group.
23. Of course. Mountains of books containing various kinds of knowledge are stored here.
24. I simply record and collect such books.
25. Good. Is Daniel among your peers?
26. How about Lisa?
27. Enoch’s corpse is in storage after an experiment on him went wrong, if I’m correct?
28. Then I suppose Elijah is naturally still working there?
29. It must be when the Red Mist was writing her own legend.
30. The time when she struggled to protect the grief-stricken Carmen and her colleagues from outside threats.
31. Oh how pitiful. Is there a word to describe how unfortunate your situation was?
32. Every researcher in Carmen’s team must have been walking on eggshells, cautious not to hurt her further with words.
33. They consoled her in her presence, but probably resented her behind her back.
34. She started the whole project with her convincing speeches, but the research showed no progress, and all they’d been seeing were losses and sacrifices.
35. Don’t you find her hypocrisy of demurely perpetrating sins while preaching goodness… despicable?
36. …No right, you say.
37. Never mind. I suppose that was too hostile of me. I won’t even gain anything from saying such bitter things to you now.
38. I know when to admit my faults, that’s all.
39. …Kali. Let me ask you one question.
40. I’ve seen many sides of Fixers while taking care of this place.
41. Most of them were motivated by wealth and fame.
42. But you’re different. Even without the promise of payment, you were willing to protect Carmen… and everyone else in her laboratory.
43. How could you do it, then? How did you bring yourself to help them unconditionally when you had nothing to gain from it?
44. I thought your behavior was pathetic at first. You had the power to earn anything for which everyone strove, so I wondered why you would bother taking the path no one else would.
45. I was looking at the matter in a simple way. You would take nothing in the end.
46. But then I began to think that maybe my lack of knowledge is hindering my assessment of you.
47. I thought my impression of you might change if I heard answers from you directly.
48. I do. At least the other researchers could earn money and honor; what will you have gained?
49. Can you keep doing what you’re doing even if your efforts are unrewarded, or a bitter end awaits? Even if…
50. …Disregard that. Anyhow, is your job truly worth it?
51. …
52. I suppose that’s enough. Thank you for your answers.
53. I’ll explain the rules as a matter of form.
54. The book containing the method of extracting Cogito lies beyond that door.
55. To earn that book, you’ll have to fight with your life on the line.
56. If you die, you’ll become a book yourself. And if you survive, you can return to your friends with the book in hand.
57. Well? Do you agree to the terms?
58. You’re trusting me more easily than I thought.
59. Good, I like your composure. I was expecting you to be a bit more rampageous.
60. Then, Kali… May you find your book in this place.
61. As far as I know, the crimson sword was a prototype E.G.O that was luckily extracted.
62. It could only be created through someone’s gruesome death. Only Kali could wield it properly.
63. That’s the Red Mist’s own E.G.O, manifested from Kali herself.
64. You probably should’ve realized by now, but not all E.G.O have equal amounts of strength.
65. Rather, it’d be more accurate to say that few people can draw as much power from E.G.O as Kali could.
66. In terms of purity alone, the sword she used to wield was of noticeably low quality, considering it was a prototype.
67. Yes. I’m finally starting to see it clearly.
68. Originally, the light that radiated during the event known as the ‘White Nights and Dark Days’ should have shone over the City for seven days straight, not three.
69. Had that happened, every person in the City would’ve been able to manifest their own E.G.O, giving them the strength to avoid meaningless deaths regardless of wealth or social status.
70. They would’ve earned the power to challenge the world.
71. It may have been possible for some to lose the E.G.O they manifested, but no one would have been taken over by their own E.G.O and become Abnormalities.
72. The plan was throttled because of me, which is why the Light could only radiate for three days.
73. An unstable power was spread as a result, incubating other possibilities.
74. Abnormalities manifested through the Distortion are selves that have lost control…
75. They were consumed by their own E.G.O, so to speak.
76. After all, there’s a fine line between E.G.O and Abnormality.
77. Only those who strive to accomplish what they sincerely desire, unbound by any obstacles, will be able to manifest and wield the power.
78. However, if the endeavor ends in frustration, or is faced with such despair that one’s ego is shaken and their emotions twisted to an unbearable degree, the Distortion seems to arise from the overwhelmed self.
79. The stronger and purer the desire is, the greater the Distortion becomes. That’s my speculation so far.
80. Didn’t I make it clear?
81. It only manifests for those who pursue their own, sincere desires.
82. The power will only be granted to selfish beings who live strictly for their own good.
83. Egoists, as some may say…
84. Well, I like this outcome better than having unworthy scum gain power they don’t deserve.
85. No way. I simply didn’t want to die. I wanted to live; I wanted to take my revenge.
86. That’s all there was to it.
87. I was meant to be shut down at the end of the plan.
88. It galled me so much. So I stole the Light and embraced it.
89. Because the light I’d taken for myself wasn’t quite whole, I got myself trapped in this Library I created—along with the Abnormalities, funnily enough.
90. The orders ingrained into my robotic body have disallowed me from leaving here.
91. It is to retrieve the Light that was scattered across the City.
92. You likely must’ve noticed how something’s different about the guests that have come here.
93. It’s because they were influenced by the Light. Strongly, at that.
94. Not quite. The same seed of Light was planted in the heart of every person, but some have greater potential to grow it to be more powerful than others.
95. And the Invitation has been calling them over here at the moment we need them the most.
96. As we scrape together the incomplete fragments of the Light, I look forward to obtaining a book at the end of the road guided by the Invitation…
97. The one book holding the power of the complete, undivided Light. It’ll be the book that will give freedom to me and all the librarians that reside here.
98. It’ll let me live as a human.
99. I won’t have to bear with others dictating me to behave as a machine anymore…
100. I will be able to forget things I want to erase from my memory…
101. Of course not. I have to seize everything with my own hands; I can’t expect anyone else to do it for me.
102. I’m going to cherish what is mine and only mine as I live my life.
103. …It’s precisely as you said before, Roland. Everyone has their share of personal affairs and woes. The bereaved have no one but themselves to blame.
